Reframe the “ambush” as a guardrail (Anubis in practice)

Anubis = orthogonal validation at transitions.
Use it to catch drift before it becomes impact, not to create it.

What this looks like in real systems

1) Auth / session flows
Transitions to guard:
	•	login → token issuance
	•	token → session
	•	refresh → extended session
	•	session → privileged action

Anubis checks (examples):
	•	Context continuity: same device posture, geo, time window?
	•	Proportionality: does a refresh suddenly grant more scope?
	•	Sequence: was MFA skipped or out-of-order?
	•	Reversibility: can we revoke/kill instantly?

Controls:
	•	short-lived tokens + rotation
	•	step-up auth on sensitive transitions
	•	device binding / risk scoring
	•	instant revocation hooks

⸻

2) Key management / signing
Transitions to guard:
	•	generate → store (HSM/secure enclave)
	•	store → use (signing)
	•	use → delegate (API/service)
	•	rotate → revoke/recover

Anubis checks:
	•	Mechanism vs narrative: “routine rotation” actually matches rotation mechanics?
	•	Authority jump: small request → high-impact signature?
	•	Timing: unusual signing bursts?

Controls:
	•	HSM-backed keys (no raw key exposure)
	•	threshold/multi-party approvals for high-impact signs
	•	strict audit + anomaly alerts at “sign” boundary
	•	just-in-time credentials (no long-lived power)

⸻

3) Data pipelines (ingest → transform → act)
Transitions to guard:
	•	ingest → parse
	•	parse → transform
	•	transform → model/decision
	•	decision → action

Anubis checks:
	•	Meaning preservation: did schema/semantics drift?
	•	Coherence: does output match statistical/logic expectations?
	•	Reversibility: can we roll back bad outputs?

Controls:
	•	schema validation + contracts
	•	data lineage + checksums
	•	canary/holdout validation before action
	•	circuit breakers on anomalous outputs

